%%[4.1]
<TEXT>athābhiṣecanaṃ kuryād{ }ātmaśiṣyasya deśikaḥ |</TEXT>
<TEXT>sādhyasiddhyartham{ }ekasya niyogāyāparasya ca || 4:1 ||</TEXT>%
%%
<TRANS>Now the teacher should perform consecration for a disciple of his for the purpose of accomplishing the powers that he aims to attain (<foreign>sādhyasiddhyartham</foreign>) [so that he becomes a <foreign>sādhaka</foreign>],
and [also] (<foreign>ca</foreign>) one other [disciple] to take on his duties [as <foreign>ācārya</foreign>] (<foreign>niyogāya</foreign>).</TRANS>
<PARAL> The verses that follow, 4.2--8 have been quoted without attribution in
Jñānaratnāvalī T. 231:407--408.</PARAL>


%%[4.2]
<TEXT>tripadārthāṃ catuḥpādāṃ bhuktimuktiphalodayām |</TEXT>
<TEXT>saṃhitāṃ yo vijānāti śiṣyo 'sau śekam{ }arhati ||</TEXT>

<TRANS>One who knows a scripture (<foreign>saṃhitām</foreign>) with its three topics and four <foreign>pāda</foreign>s, which abounds in the fruits of supernatural and liberation, such a disciple merits consecration.</TRANS>
<PARAL>Quoted with attribution to Brahmaśambhu in ĪŚGDP KP p. 184, 3--5; qu. without attr. in KKD p. 369 (variant °phalapradām) (SŚP III 457).  Also quoted, without attribution, in the <sktw>Jñānaratnāvalī</sktw> on p. 369 of the GOML MS. It is quoted with attribution to the <sktw>Mṛgendra</sktw> in the <sktw>Dīkṣādarśa</sktw> (IFP T. 153, p. 431), and indeed the beginning of Brahmaśambhu's verse echoes <sktw>Mṛgendratantra</sktw> 2:2.VP
</PARAL>
<NOTE>In the bottom margin, there are two glosses, one for <foreign>tripadārthām</foreign>, which reads <foreign>pati paśu pāśa</foreign>, and one for <foreign>catuḥpādām</foreign>, which reads <foreign>jñāna kriyā caryā yoga</foreign>.</NOTE>

%%[4.3]
%%\msK 66v1=?? (PDF)

<TEXT>sa <FOLIO>66v</FOLIO> ca mantrī guruś{ }ceti dvidhokto vṛttibhedataḥ |</TEXT>
<TEXT>manāk{ }tadvyaktaye samyag{ }ucyate lakṣaṇaṃ tayoḥ ||</TEXT>

<TRANS>That person (<foreign>saḥ</foreign>) is said to be of two kinds, according to his way of life: a Mantra-specialist [viz.\ a <foreign>sādhaka</foreign>] or a Guru.  In order to expand on this slightly, a correct (<foreign>samyak</foreign>) definition of both will given [below].</TRANS>
%% Sathyanarayanan would prefer: In order to expand on this, a definition of the two will be briefly stated correctly.

%%[4.4]
<TEXT>tatra deśaguṇākārabhaktiśaktikriyānvitaḥ |</TEXT>
%%\msK 66v2= ?? (PDF)
<TEXT>hiṃsānugrahayor{ }nityam{ }aprasaktaḥ sahāyavān ||</TEXT>
<APP>\vd <LEM>aprasaktaḥ</LEM> \emend; aprasakta \msA<\APP>
<TRANS>Among those two (<foreign>tatra</foreign>), [the first] should have the [requisite] place/provenance, qualities, body, devotion, capacity and [regular habit of] ritual practice.
He should always be detached from both agression and compassion.  He should have a ritual assistant (<foreign>sahāyavān</foreign>).</TRANS>

<NOTE>It is not clear whether deśa refers to the notion that the <foreign>sādhaka</foreign> should come only from suitable places, in other words none of the regions beginning with K, for instance, or whether it refers to him having a suitable place for practising his <foreign>sādhana</foreign>.

He is described as <foreign>sahāyavān</foreign> not simply because he should have friends, but because he must have a ritual assistant, variously referred to in early Mantramārga literature as a <foreign>sahāya</foreign>, <foreign>sakhāya</foreign>, or <foreign>uttarasādhaka</foreign>.
</NOTE>

%%[4.5]
<TEXT>sthiradhīḥ satvasaṃpanno jitadvaṃdvo ’calendriyaḥ |</TEXT>
<TEXT>anivarttitābhiyogaś{ }ca sādhakaḥ syād{ }dṛḍhavrataḥ ||</TEXT>
<APP>\vd <LEM>sādhakaḥ</LEM> \emend; sādhaka \msA<\APP>

<TRANS>He should be of firm mind, endowed with courage; he must have overcome extremes [of for example hot and cold], with senses that are not flighty.  He should be one whose dedication cannot be deflected.  [Such a person] may be a <foreign>sādhaka</foreign>, firm in [his committment to his] religious observances (<foreign>dṛḍhavrataḥ</foreign>).</TRANS>

<PARAL>The pāda \textit{anivarttitābhiyogaś ca} is hypermetrical.
	Jñ has anivṛttābhiyogaś ca, which is metrically correct. Jñ
	has an extra line after this: \textit{guruś caivaṃvidhaḥ kiṃ
	tu sumūrttiḥ śrutaśīlavān}.</PARAL>
%
%%[4.6]
<TEXT>na hīnāṃgo ’dhikāṅgaś{ }ca nātidīrgho na vāmanaḥ |</TEXT>
<TEXT>nātikṛṣṇo na gauraś{ }ca nātisthūlo na vā tanuḥ ||</TEXT>

<TRANS>He should not have too few limbs, nor too many; he should not be too tall, nor a dwarf; he should not be too dark nor too fair, nor too fat, nor too thin.</TRANS>

